JOHANNESBURG - The rand was slightly firmer on Tuesday afternoon despite SA s economy having contracted in the last quarter of 2016.Gross domestic product (GDP) for the fourth quarter was 0.3% down on the previous quarter s versus the market expectation of a 0.6% contraction.The South African economy contracted by 0,3% in Q4:2016 #GDP https://t.co/5apHDMZfzj pic.twitter.com/whcKFbpqprThe negative GDP performance was due largely to mining contracting 11.5% and manufacturing contracting 3.1%.READ: GDP - Fall in mining production puts SA economy in slumpAn interesting aspect of GPD figures was the extent of recovery in agricultural output which had been in recession for two years. Stats SA said the industry s decline of 0 1% in the fourth quarter of 2016 was mainly the result of decreases in the production of horticultural products.The economy grew 0.3% in 2016. MMI Investments and Savings economist Sanisha Packirisamy said GDP had bottomed in 2016 and the growth rate should improve to about 1% in 2017 and 2% in 2018.NW recorded highest provincial growth in 2015 at 4,9% mainly due to rebound in #mining sector #GDP https://t.co/Z0wow1VK3t pic.twitter.com/mH3dTZgaqKPackirisamy said higher expected global economic growth should provide a slightly more supportive environment for SA s export activity. A recovery of nearly 20% in global commodity prices over the past 12 months boded well for a mild uptick in SA s beleaguered mining and manufacturing sectors.At 3.30pm the rand was R12.9524 to the dollar from Monday s R13.0137 R13.6985 to the euro from R13.7717 and R15.8043 to the pound from R15.9290.The euro was at $1.0575 from $1.0582.Economist Xhanti Phayi weighs in on what the low growth figure means.iNet Bridge